<p>Photos do two jobs at once. They make customers trust you before they call, and they tell Google your business is real and active.</p>

<p>Google's own numbers back this up: businesses with photos on their profile get 42% more direction requests and 35% more website clicks. For a home service company, where every customer is comparing you against two or three competitors on the map, that gap decides real jobs.</p>

<p>Most owners treat profile photos as a one-time setup chore. Upload a logo, add a few truck pictures, done. This post covers what a working photo system looks like instead: what to shoot on every job, how to set up your profile, and the small habits that turn a camera roll into rankings.</p>

<h2>Rule Number One: Real Photos Only</h2>

<p>No stock, ever. Stock photos consistently underperform real ones, both in rankings and in trust. A slightly crooked phone photo of your actual crew beats a polished stock image every time, because customers can tell the difference and so can Google.</p>

<p>This is good news if you think about it. The thing that works best is also the thing only you can produce.</p>

<h2>The Five-Minute Shot List</h2>

<p>The habit that matters: five minutes of photos per job, every job. Here is what to capture.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Before and after, same angle.</strong> Stand in the same spot for both. The pair is the single most convincing image you can put anywhere.</li>
<li><strong>The crew at work.</strong> Real people in real gear, faces visible when possible. This is what separates you from every faceless competitor.</li>
<li><strong>The equipment.</strong> The truck, the machine, the rig. Serious equipment signals a serious operation.</li>
<li><strong>Context shots.</strong> Wide frames that show the house, the yard, the street. These carry location signals and feel local because they are.</li>
<li><strong>The cleanup.</strong> A spotless site after the job answers the question every homeowner silently asks.</li>
</ul>

<p>A few phone camera basics make all of these better. Wipe the lens first; half of all bad job photos are just a dirty lens. Shoot in daylight with the sun behind you. Hold the phone level and grab both landscape and portrait versions of your best shots. Skip the filters, since natural photos read as honest. And leave Location Services on for your camera. That last one matters more than it sounds, and we'll come back to it.</p>

<h2>Setting Up Your Profile Photos</h2>

<p>Before anything else: never delete your existing profile photos. Old photos carry views and engagement that help you. Leave them alone and optimize everything you add from today forward.</p>

<p>Then fill every slot Google gives you:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Cover photo (1024 x 575 minimum).</strong> Your best action shot: crew working, truck on site. This is the image Google shows first.</li>
<li><strong>Logo (720 x 720 minimum).</strong> Clean logo on a plain background, so you are recognizable next to your name.</li>
<li><strong>Team (3 or more).</strong> The owner, the crew, group shots. Faces build trust faster than anything else on the profile.</li>
<li><strong>At work (3 or more).</strong> Jobs in progress and finished results. This is the category you add to constantly from the shot list above.</li>
<li><strong>Exterior and equipment (3 or more).</strong> The shop, the yard, the trucks. Proof of a real, established operation.</li>
</ul>

<p>Every photo needs to be under 10MB and at least 720 x 720. A profile with 20 or more real photos is the baseline we set for every client. The profiles that win their markets keep climbing well past 100.</p>

<h2>Upload Rhythm Beats Upload Volume</h2>

<p>Two photos a week, every week, outperforms forty photos dumped once a quarter.</p>

<p>Upload frequency is an activity signal, the same way <a href="/blog/how-to-get-more-google-reviews/">review frequency</a> is. A profile that added photos steadily all year reads as a business people are hiring right now. A profile that got a big photo dump eight months ago reads as a business that lost interest.</p>

<p>Put it on the calendar: every Friday, pick the two best shots from that week's jobs and post them to the profile. That is the entire system.</p>

<h2>Geotagging and File Names</h2>

<p>Here is where Location Services pays off. Photos taken on a phone with it turned on already carry GPS coordinates in the file. Google strips that data after reading it, which means it costs you nothing and can only help. If you upload from a computer, free tools like GeoImgr can write coordinates onto a photo before you post it.</p>

<p>One warning: tag the photo where the job actually happened, never anywhere else. Faking locations is the kind of shortcut that gets profiles suspended.</p>

<p>File names are the same idea in smaller form. Before uploading, rename the file from IMG_4823.jpg to something true and descriptive: oak-removal-wake-forest.jpg. It is a small signal, it takes five seconds, and it stacks up across hundreds of photos.</p>

<h2>Bonus: Put the Same Photos to Work on Your Website</h2>

<p>Everything above is about your Google Business Profile, but the library it builds pays a second time on your website. Three habits if you reuse it there:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Alt text on every image</strong> that describes what is actually in it, service and city included when honest.</li>
<li><strong>Compress to modern formats</strong> like webp so pages stay fast. Big raw photos are the number one cause of slow home service websites.</li>
<li><strong>Keep it consistent.</strong> The same real photos across your website, profile, and social pages read as one trustworthy business to the AI search tools now reading all three.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What This Looks Like in Practice</h2>

<p>Five minutes of photos on every job using the shot list. Two uploads to the profile every Friday. Files named honestly and tagged where the work happened. The same real images feeding the website and socials.</p>

<p>None of it requires a photographer or new software. Six months of that builds a photo library no competitor can fake, because they would have to do the jobs to get the pictures.</p>

